This article first appeared at southern weekend and is not to be reprinted without permission

By Zhou Xiaoling, southern weekly reporter

Southern weekend intern, Ye Zi

Editor in chief | Zhang Yue

On February 9,2020, the study, "clinical characteristics of COVID-19 infection in China in 2019, " led by Zhong Nanshan, a member of the Chinese Academy of Engineering and head of a high-level Expert Group of the National Health Commission, was published on the preprint website Medrxiv.

The study reviewed the clinical features of 1,099 cases of newly diagnosed pneumonia in China, of which only 1.18% had direct contact with wild animals and 31.30% had been to Wuhan, 71.80% of the patients had contact with people from Wuhan. The median incubation period of NCP was found to be 3.0 days (ranging from 0 to 24 days) and up to 24 days.

Six days ago, the Politburo Standing Committee of the Communist Party of China said that scientific research should be intensified, that "scientific and technological support is indispensable to the victory of the epidemic" and that national scientific research workers should be mobilized to participate in scientific research on the prevention and control of the epidemic, promote the open sharing of relevant data and case information.

According to a review by reporters at southern weekend, the first study of Neopneumonia to be published in the International Papers Journal database was published on January 15,2020, in a paper from the Zhejiang University titled Recent Advances in Detection of human respiratory virus infection, published in the Journal of Medical Virology.

From January 15 to February 5, Chinese scholars participated in the publication of a total of 66 articles, an average of 3.1 articles per day, a total of 590 researchers. Of these, 11 were published in top international publications.

During the period of SARS, from November 2002 to July 2003,2,295 articles related to SARS were found in Web of Science and PubMed, among which 588 articles were published by Chinese scholars, an average of 2.17 articles per day, and 680 articles were published by Chinese scholars, accounting for 119 articles, 0.44 per day.

1
21 days, 66 papers

1

###21 days, 66 papers

Since January 15,2020, the number of papers on NCP by Chinese scholars at home and abroad has gradually increased, peaking at 11 on January 29 and 9 on February 4. On January 24th, for example, five articles were published throughout the day, four of them in top international publications.

The data that southern weekend reporters queried mainly came from the "2019-nCov" scientific research dynamic monitoring platform launched by the Chinese Academy of Sciences's Wuhan Document and Information Center, as well as Journal paper platforms such as CNKI, Elsevier, Wiley Online Library.

The 66 papers can be divided into two categories according to the publishing platform: 32 papers published in professional journals, and 34 papers published on the BIORXIV preprint platform and the MEDRXIV preprint platform.

The BIORXIV preprint platform is a platform for storing and publishing medical academic papers. Papers published on the platform are not peer-reviewed and will be posted on the website within 1-2 days after they have been professionally reviewed for academic and non-academic reasons such as plagiarism, apparent errors, etc. . The published papers have a single electronic identifier, which can be retrieved and referenced, and the latter does not affect the formal publication. The MEDRXIV preprint platform is also a platform for preprint distribution of medical research papers.

Of the published articles, 11 were published in top global publications and 21 were published in other journals, the 21 articles were published in the Journal of Medical Virology, China Knowledge Network, SSRN Social Science Research Network, Travel Medicine and Infectious Disease, Emerging Microbes & Infections, Journal of Virology, Journal of Virology, Journal of Infection, Science China Life, and Radiology.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Data collation: Southern Weekend reporter Zhou Xiaoling and southern weekend intern ye Zi. The deadline is Feb. 5

2
Influencing factors of "four top medical journals"

2

###Influencing factors of "four top medical journals"

The The New England Journal of Medicine (Nejm) , the Lancet, the Jama (Jama) and the British Medical Journal (BMJ) are among the world's "top four medical journals" .

Of the 66 papers, eight were published in the top four journals and three in the top scientific journal Nature.

Two of them, The New England Journal of Medicine, are from China's Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.

The first author of two of the six articles in the Lancet was from Wuhan Jinyintan Hospital, two from the Li Ka Shing Faculty of Medicine, and one from the Chinese Center for Disease Control and Prevention, the authors of the last one are Wang Chen, academician of the Chinese Academy of Engineering, President of the Chinese Academy of Medical Sciences and Academician of the Chinese Academy of Sciences, Takatomi, director of the Chinese Center for Disease Control and Prevention, and medical experts from the University of Oxford and the University of Virginia, it's a commentary on the new coronary pneumonia in Wuhan.

Two of the first authors of the three nature articles were Shi Zhengli of the Chinese Academy of Sciences, the lead author of the paper was Zhang Yongzhen of the Fudan University and the public health. It is worth noting that professor Zhang Yongzhen is also a researcher at the Institute of Medical Science.

Articles published in top journals mean different things to researchers.

According to the latest impact factor published on June 20,2019, the SCI had the highest impact factor of 70.67 in the Journal The New England Journal of Medicine, followed by the Lancet (59.1) and nature (43.07) , journal of Infectious Diseases (5.099) , Journal of Journal of Virology (4.324) , the most published journal of Medical Virology by Chinese scholars is 2.049.

In academic research, the term "impact factor" refers to the average number of citations of a journal published in the previous two years in the current year. The higher the influence factor is, the higher the citation rate is, and the higher the influence of the research results published by the Journal, the higher the academic level is.

A university researcher in the field told southern weekend that "The New England Journal of Medicine is a high score with 70 influencing factors, and some institutions will award tens of thousands of Yuan. "

An industry insider who once worked at China's top three hospitals said the paper was published to explain and publish scientific research results, which are now determined by the number and quality of papers published around the world.

She explains that if you publish an SCI article, a paper published in a journal that has been included in the SCI (Scientific Citation Index, Science Citation Index) , virtually every medical institution has a written reward.

In one of the top journals, there are also sections. Take, for example, the Lancet, whose catalogue includes research paper and case report. "At the moment, the CDC doesn't Publish Scientific Studies, it publishes case reports, which means 'get information about a patient's treatment and get it out there, ' and that's an article. "

According to his observation, research papers do not dominate in Science, with "case reports" , "scientific history reviews" and "advertisements" accounting for 60 per cent. Because case reports are first-hand information, they are also faster to review than research papers.

In order to encourage researchers to launch research results in response to the outbreak of new coronavirus pneumonia, the National Natural Science Foundation of China launched the new coronavirus pneumonia research project on January 22, to Fund research into the outbreak for a period of two years, with 20 projects of $1.5 million each.

The next day, the Ministry of Science and Technology of the People's Republic of China launched an emergency scientific research project on the new coronavirus epidemic, including 15 members of the Expert Group. On that day, eight emergency research projects were launched and funds were allocated. On the same day, the Chinese Academy of Sciences, led by the virus, a multi-institutional joint, set up 13 experts composed of the emergency expert group.

3
"The way to publish data is to publish papers. "

3

###"The way to publish data is to publish papers. "

According to southern weekend's calculations, as many as 590 Chinese researchers participated in the 66 articles. According to the author's unit, can be divided into universities, scientific research institutions, CDC and hospitals in four categories.

Among them, 45% of the university population involved 43 universities at home and abroad, 20% involved CDC, 17 involved CDC at national, provincial, municipal and district levels, 18% involved hospitals, and Wuhan Jinyintan Hospital had the largest number of participants. Research institutions accounted for 17% .

Among universities and research institutions, 11 were published by the Chinese Academy of Sciences, 8 by Fudan, 9 by the University of Hong Kong and 3 by the Capital University of Medical Sciences.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The CDC stands out in terms of the number and quality of published papers.

In addition to the CDC, 14 provincial and city level CDC published the COVID-19 paper, including the provincial level CDC in Hubei, Guangdong, Hunan, Guizhou and Inner Mongolia; The municipal level includes the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention in Wuhan, Jingzhou, Chengdu, Anyang, Panjin, Nanchang and Xianyang; the district level includes the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention in Jiading District and Jiading District; and the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention in the PLA.

The Chinese Center for Disease Control and Prevention was founded in 2002 as The Chinese Academy of Preventive Medicine. Li Liming, former director of the Chinese Center for Disease Control and Prevention, was quoted by the China Health News as saying that the CDC was set up to allow researchers to conduct scientific research aimed at controlling diseases and solving public health problems.

At present, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) has published 11 articles in English. Of these, two were published in the Journal The New England Journal of Medicine, two in nature, one in the Lancet, one in the SSRN social science research network, and three in the BIORXIV preprint edition, 2 published on the preprint platform of MEDRXIV. The first-hand patient data were used as a sample in the 6 official english-language articles published by CDC at all levels.

One of the advantages of the CDC's collection of papers is the availability of data.

A phd student in Public Health told southern weekend that her college has a faculty recruiting team that crawls data from the Internet to write papers, "It's all about having ideas, not having data, and having to toil to get data from the Internet. It's all about who has the database. ".

The university researcher said China's outbreak, the CDC must first report to the World Health Organization (WHO) , "for research institutions, the way to open data is to publish papers. ".

4
Questions remain about the source of the virus

4

###Questions remain about the source of the virus

From the research content, these papers, in Infectious Disease Epidemic Prediction, drug research and development, virus detection and genetic analysis, clinical data research and so on have breakthroughs.

Specifically, 26 articles on Infectious Disease Prediction, 20 articles on virus analysis, 9 articles on clinical data analysis, and 6 articles on drug development were the most concentrated. There are 5 pieces of expert opinion and information in non-research papers.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
In terms of viral genetic analysis, as early as January 10,2020, zhang Yongzhen, a professor at the Chinese CDC, the Fudan University and the public health, published the genome sequence of the COVID-19 outbreak in Wuhan in Genbank for researchers to download, use and analyze, it also states that if you want to publish the results of your use of data, you need to contact them.

On January 22,2020, Gao Shan, a professor in the Life Sciences Department of Nankai University, caused professor Zhang's dissatisfaction when his team published the results of the study in the journal Bioinformatics after using the Genomic data that professor Zhang had made public, and demand an immediate retraction.

In response, Gao responded to southern weekend reporters that data on major public health events needs to be shared, that no one has ownership of the data, and that the CDC needs to be open to the public in the first place. As of press time, Professor Zhang Yongzhen has not yet responded to the southern weekend reporter's interview email.

The original analysis of viral genes by Shi Zhengli's team of Wuhan Virus Institute, which has attracted much attention, was published on the BIORXIV preprint platform on January 23, the full genetic sequence of the virus in five patients was traced by the Chinese Academy of Sciences Virus Research Institute, Jinyintan Hospital in Wuhan and the Hubei Provincial Center for Disease Control, the sequences of coronaviruses in bats are 96% consistent.

Recently, an Indian researcher published an article on the platform saying that the COVID-19 contains four specific insertion sequences, some of which are similar to HIV, arousing public suspicion, the finger of blame is pointed at Wuhan Virus Institute.

On Feb. 2, Shi responded to a text message sent by a southern weekly reporter, saying, "I don't think it's worth my while to believe that bad media in the United States are spreading rumors and that scientists who believe that India has no bottom line are suspicious. " On the same day, Shi made a similar point in his circle of friends, and attached is the news of the retraction by the Indian scholar.

The next day, Shi's team, whose work was published earlier on the BIORXIV preprint platform and published in nature, proposed that the COVID-19 uses the same cells as the SARS-CoV to enter the receptor ACE2(angiotensin converting enzyme 2) .

According to the latest research results, the current discussion of viral genetic analysis has not been fully answered, especially for the virus transmission intermediate host analysis is still not clear answer.

In addition, the source of the virus and other questions, the answer is still unclear.

In The Lancet, Scripps Research Institute's Evolutionary Biology Christiane Andson speculates that there is a possibility that the infected could have brought the virus to the south China seafood market, meaning it could have originated elsewhere, to the south China Seafood Market, where it broke out on a massive scale. Among the first 41 patients in Wuhan, 14 had no history of exposure to the south China seafood market.

Similarly, a paper published on Jan. 29 by China's multi level, 14 centers for Disease Control and prevention found that 55 percent of cases that occurred before Jan. 1,2020, were associated with the south China Seafood Wholesale Market.

In drug research. On February 4, Wuhan Virus Institute, the latest research found that Remdesivir and chloroquine in vitro control of 2019-nCoV infection effective.

On Jan. 21, the Chinese Academy of Sciences filed a patent for Remdesivir's Chinese invention, aimed at countering 2019 COVID-19, according to public filings. It will enter major countries through the PCT (patent cooperation agreement) , but whether it can be applied for or not is uncertain.

On the afternoon of February 5, according to Xinhua News Agency, Ridgway completed the registration and approval of clinical trials with the support of the National Health and State Food and Drug Administration and other departments, the first serious patients with COVID-19 pneumonia will try the drug on February 6.

Studying the virus is difficult. In the blood and plague, a nonfiction account of the Zaire Ebolavirus, he wrote, "In biology, there is no such thing as 100 per cent certainty, everything is so complicated, everything is so complicated, and every time you think you know something, you peel back a layer of confusion and discover that there is a deeper layer of complexity underneath. Nature has nothing to do with simplicity."

(southern weekend reporter Gao Yichen contributed to this report.)
